Following domestication c. 8500 cal. BP (
 
  24
 ), millet farmers began a westward expansion that resulted in the spread of millet products to the eastern margins of the Tibetan Plateau between 5400 and 4400 cal. BP (movies S3 and S4) (
 
  25
 ). Broomcorn millet (and potentially foxtail millet) begins to appear at sites throughout Central Asia following 4000 cal. BP (
 
  7
 ).
